# Wallerstein’s Core-Periphery Systems Model
- World system theory
- Breaks countries into [[Flashcards/Social Studies/APHG/Unit 4/Core States\|Core States]], [[Flashcards/Social Studies/APHG/Periphery States\|Periphery States]], and [[Semi-Periphery States\|Semi-Periphery States]] 
- **Roles may have changed over time—theory based on 1970s** 
![world systems theory.gif|no-float](/img/user/Files/world%20systems%20theory.gif) ![[World_trade_map.PNG|no-float]]
# [[400 Social Studies/410 AP Human Geography/Unit 3/Modules 18-24/Module 21#Colonialism and Imperialism\|Colonialism]] and the **Berlin Conference**
- European countries wanted to be empires **([[400 Social Studies/410 AP Human Geography/Unit 3/Modules 18-24/Module 21#Colonialism and Imperialism\|imperialism]])**, so they either settled in new places or took the [[Flashcards/Social Studies/APHG/Unit 1/Natural Resources\|resources]] from new places **([[400 Social Studies/410 AP Human Geography/Unit 3/Modules 18-24/Module 21#Colonialism and Imperialism\|colonialism]])**.
	- **They don’t want to waste money on wars with each other, so they try to peacefully establish “spheres of influence”.**
- At this conference in Berlin in 1884, they divided up Africa.
	- Example of **[[Flashcards/Social Studies/APHG/Unit 4/Core States\|core states]]** and their relationship to **[[Flashcards/Social Studies/APHG/Periphery States\|peripheral states]].**

- No African role/say in mapping.
- Their goal was to divide resource-rich land and coastal land for transport.
- These lines **divided ethnicities (shared ancestry and cultural tradition, leading to shared identity).**
	- These ethnicities, as they gain a desire for recognition and self-determination, form nationalities ([[Flashcards/Social Studies/APHG/Unit 4/Nation\|nations]]).
# [[Flashcards/Social Studies/APHG/Unit 4/Nation\|Nations]]
- The **foundation of most [[Flashcards/Social Studies/APHG/Unit 4/Nation\|nations]] is a shared [[Flashcards/Social Studies/APHG/Unit 3/Ethnicity\|Ethnicity]], but may also be related to a shared religion, language, or other attributes like historical bonds.**
- **[[Flashcards/Social Studies/APHG/Unit 4/Nation\|Nations]] seek some degree of recognition,** often political autonomy or greater control within the [[Flashcards/Social Studies/APHG/Unit 1/Region\|Region]] they live.
# [[Flashcards/Social Studies/APHG/Unit 4/State\|States]]
- ==Remember: states = countries.==
